# Page defaults — ghl-design-previews

These rules govern how new pages, components, and assets are added to
this repo. They exist so previews stay consistent and so adding a new
mockup is a 30-second job, not a 30-minute one.

## First principle: copy from upstream, don't invent

**Every artifact in this repo has an upstream code repo.** Pages
come from `spm-ts`. Shells come from `spm-ts`. HighRise primitives
come from `@platform-ui/highrise`. Tailwind config, PostCSS config,
and build wiring follow `spm-ts`'s conventions. Tokens come from
HR's compiled `style.css`.

**Copy verbatim.** Don't infer from a screenshot. Don't translate
"what looks similar." Don't re-derive in HR tokens because they
feel cleaner. Don't fix typos. Don't simplify weird prod patterns.
Match what ships, even when it's ugly.

**If the upstream is missing something — stop and ask.** Examples
of "missing":
- A nav item appears in a screenshot but isn't in `spm-ts/src/util/navigation.ts`
- An HR primitive prop is needed but isn't in our local stub
- A Tailwind plugin in `spm-ts`'s config has no Vite equivalent
- An asset path resolves to a private CDN we can't reach
- A component imports a Vuex store / i18n key the preview doesn't have

Surface the gap. Don't fill it with invented values, plausible
defaults, or "modern" alternatives.

**Why this exists:** a previous pass fabricated the entire ShellV1
sidebar and topbar from screenshots. It looked plausible and was
completely wrong. Worse, the result was useless to dev — class
names didn't match prod, so dev couldn't have lifted the markup
back into `spm-ts`. Fidelity work was double-discarded. This rule
keeps the previews in lockstep with what dev actually ships, so
both stakeholders see the truth **and** dev can reuse what we
build.

## Where things come from

This repo is downstream of `spm-ts`. There are two kinds of work:

1. **Page content** (e.g. `AddOnsPage.vue`) — copy verbatim from the
   matching `spm-ts/src/pmd/pages/...` file. Only the imports and the
   shell wrapper change. Don't edit copy, structure, or styles unless
   the user explicitly asks.
2. **The shell** (sidebar + topbar) — vendor verbatim from spm-ts.
   The spm-ts shell predates the HR design system and uses its own
   global stylesheets + Tailwind utility classes (`@apply` directives
   in `styles.sidebar.scss`).

   **The canonical files for ShellV1:**
   - `spm-ts/src/pmd/components/sidebar/SideBar.vue` — sidebar template
   - `spm-ts/src/pmd/components/sidebar/UIMenuItems.vue` — nav-row template
   - `spm-ts/src/pmd/components/sidebar/LocationSwitcherContainer.vue` — location pill
   - `spm-ts/src/pmd/components/sidebar/QuickActions.vue` — search + quick-actions row
   - `spm-ts/src/pmd/components/TopBar.vue` — topbar template
   - `spm-ts/src/assets/pmd/css/styles.sidebar.scss` — the visual rules
   - `spm-ts/src/assets/pmd/css/styles.sidebar.light.scss` — light theme overrides
   - `spm-ts/src/util/navigation.ts` lines 10780–11650 — the agency-mode nav array
   - `spm-ts/src/assets/pmd/img/{agency,location}-marker.svg` — location-pill icons

   These files live in the user's local `~/Desktop/Projects/spm-ts/`
   working copy. If they're missing, **stop and ask**. Do not make up
   class names, colors, paddings, or nav items from screenshots.

## Shell

- **New page requests default to wrapping `<ShellV1>`.** Override only
  when the user explicitly says "V2", "ShellV2", or "no shell".
  - `<ShellV1>` lives at `src/shells/ShellV1/index.vue` and renders
    sidebar + topbar matching production spm-ts.
  - Pass `active="<nav-meta-key>"` (matching the `meta` field in the
    spm-ts nav array — e.g. `agency-marketplace` for Add-Ons) so the
    correct row is highlighted.
- `<ShellV2>` is a placeholder until Phase 2 ships. Don't try to flesh
  it out without an explicit task to do so.
- "No shell" pages (e.g. the index landing) render their own surface
  full-bleed without a shell wrapper.
- **The shell requires `<body data-theme="default-dark-v1">`** in
  `index.html`. Many sidebar/topbar dark-theme rules vendored from
  spm-ts's `PMDApp.vue` style block are scoped to that attribute.
  Without it, the rules don't apply and the shell silently degrades.
  Don't remove the attribute without understanding what breaks.
- **Two style blocks in `src/App.vue` are vendored verbatim from
  `spm-ts/src/pmd/PMDApp.vue`'s `<style>` blocks** (lines 722–944
  upstream). They define `.pmd-app .hl_wrapper` padding, the `:root`
  CSS-variable block the shell depends on, and the
  `body[data-theme='default-dark-v1']` rules. Edit upstream first,
  then re-vendor — don't hand-edit ours in isolation.
- **Three legacy stylesheets are deliberately not vendored**:
  `styles.css` (29,287 lines), `styles.patch.css` (3,432 lines),
  `styles.patch.scss` (41 lines). All three are V1-sidebar-era global
  CSS with zero `sidebar-v2` selectors. We're previewing V2 only.
  If a future preview needs V1 chrome, vendor them then — don't
  silently re-skip on a subsequent port.

## Files & routing

- Pages live in `src/pages/` with **PascalCase** filenames
  (e.g. `AddOnsPage.vue`, `PageTabs.vue`).
- Routes are added to `src/routes.ts` with **kebab-case** paths
  (`/add-ons`, `/page-tabs`). Use lazy imports
  (`() => import('@/pages/Foo.vue')`) so each preview is its own
  chunk.
- Each new route gets a `meta.title` and `meta.summary` — the index
  page reads these to render the preview list. Set `meta.shell`
  to `'V1'` or `'V2'` so the index card shows the right pill.

## Tokens & styling — **page content only**

This section governs styles **inside the page slot of `<ShellV1>`**.
For the shell itself, see "Source of truth" above.

- Use HighRise tokens from `src/tokens.css` for page content. Names
  match production HR exactly: `--gray-50`, `--primary-600`,
  `--success-200`, `--warning-500`, etc.
- Don't hardcode hex values in page styles. Literals allowed:
  - `#ffffff` (the only literal white we use)
  - `rgba(...)` shadow tints (`rgba(16, 24, 40, 0.x)` — HR doesn't
    expose RGB channels for shadow tinting).
- If a page needs a token that isn't in `tokens.css`, ask before
  inventing one.
- For HR component / token questions, the source of truth is
  `HIGHRISE_DS.md` at the repo root.

## HighRise stubs

- HR primitives live at `src/components/highrise/` (`HLTabs`,
  `HLTabPane`, `HLButton`, `HLTag`). Import via the barrel:
  `import { HLTabs, HLTabPane } from '@/components/highrise'`.
- These are **stubs** — they render the HR visual treatment with HR
  tokens but only support the props the migrated pages actually use.
- If a page needs an HR primitive that isn't here yet, **ask first**.
  Adding a stub is fine; reaching for a third-party component library
  or copying half of `@platform-ui/highrise` into the repo is not.

## Icons

- **Page-content icons:** Font Awesome 5.8.1 (loaded via CDN in
  `index.html` to match what spm-ts ships). Use
  `<i class="fas fa-..."/>` with FA 5 names. Avoid FA 6 — names
  sometimes drift between versions.
- **Shell nav icons:** prod uses a mix of CDN-hosted SVG URLs
  (`https://cdn.msgsndr.com/sidebar-v2/...svg`) and Font Awesome 5
  unicode glyphs rendered via prod's `sm-button` CSS-variable trick.
  Both come straight from `spm-ts/src/util/navigation.ts`. Don't
  swap an SVG URL for a similar-looking FA name (or vice versa) —
  that's how previous ports drifted.

## Dependencies

- Runtime stack is fixed: **Vue 3, Vite, vue-router, TypeScript,
  Font Awesome 5.8.1 (CDN)**.
- **Build-time deps mirror spm-ts at pinned versions** (no `^` caret
  ranges — bumping a version is a deliberate act, not a side effect).
  Update these in lockstep when spm-ts upgrades:

  | Package                     | Version  | Source                       |
  | --------------------------- | -------- | ---------------------------- |
  | `tailwindcss`               | `3.4.14` | spm-ts/package.json          |
  | `postcss`                   | `8.5.6`  | spm-ts/package.json          |
  | `autoprefixer`              | `10.4.20`| spm-ts/package.json          |
  | `sass`                      | `1.85.1` | spm-ts/package.json          |
  | `@tailwindcss/forms`        | `0.5.3`  | spm-ts/package.json          |
  | `@tailwindcss/typography`   | `0.5.7`  | spm-ts/package.json          |
  | `@tailwindcss/aspect-ratio` | `0.4.2`  | spm-ts/package.json          |
  | `postcss-nesting`           | `10.2.0` | spm-ts/package.json          |

- **One deliberate divergence from spm-ts:** spm-ts uses
  `"vite": "npm:rolldown-vite@latest"` (an experimental Rust-based
  Vite fork). We stay on regular `vite@6.x`. Reason: rolldown-vite is
  alpha, unstable, and changes nothing about the styling pipeline.
  If a future spm-ts capability requires rolldown specifically, we
  revisit then.
- **Don't add other npm dependencies without asking.** That includes
  UI libraries, icon packs, animation libs, utility libs.

## Imports & boundaries

- **No runtime imports** from `spm-ts/`, `@platform-ui/*`,
  `@gohighlevel/*`, or any other private package. The deployed bundle
  must be standalone.
- **Build-time vendoring is the supported path** for the shell.
  Specifically: copying SCSS from `spm-ts/src/assets/pmd/css/` and
  SVG icons from `spm-ts/src/assets/pmd/img/` into
  `src/assets/spm-shell/` is how we keep visual fidelity.
- Use the `@/` alias for in-repo imports:
  `import Foo from '@/pages/Foo.vue'`.

## Copy

- Outcome-driven, WHY → WHAT → HOW (tagline tells the buyer why,
  title tells them what, benefits tell them how). Each benefit ties
  to an outcome, not a spec.
- Use parallel structure across bullets in the same list.
- No jargon, no acronyms without first-mention definition (use
  `<abbr title="...">` for inline expansion).
- Sentence case for UI labels, not Title Case.

## Source-of-truth & reverse-sync

- Each preview's source-of-truth is recorded in `README.md` and in
  the route's `meta.summary`. Examples:
  - `AddOnsPage.vue` → source-of-truth = `spm-ts`. Designs in this
    repo are downstream — production code stays canonical.
  - `PageTabs.vue` → source-of-truth = this repo. Phase 2 mockup,
    not yet in production.
- When porting from spm-ts, change **only** the imports and the
  shell wrapper. Do not edit copy, structure, or styles unless the
  user explicitly asks.
